{"title_page": "Fiji Link", "text_new": "{{about|the Fijian domestic airline|the international Fijian airline|Fiji Airways}}\n{{Infobox airline\n| airline        = Fiji Link\n| logo           =\n| IATA           = FJ\n| ICAO           = FJA\n| callsign       = LINK FIJI\n| founded        = 2006\n| commenced      = 2006\n| ceased         = \n| hubs           = [[Nadi International Airport]]\n| secondary_hubs = [[Nausori International Airport]]\n| focus_cities   = \n| frequent_flyer = \n| lounge         = \n| alliance       = \n| subsidiaries   = \n| fleet_size     = 7\n| destinations   = 16 (see below)\n| parent         = [[Fiji Airways]]\n| company_slogan = Best value under the Sun\n| headquarters   = [[Nadi International Airport]]<br />[[Nadi]], [[Fiji]]\n| key_people     = Shaenaz Voss (Executive General Manager)\n| website        = {{url|fijiairways.com}}\n}}\n[[File:Landing on Malololailai, Fiji, 1986 - Flickr - PhillipC.jpg|thumb|Sunflower Airlines ''[[Britten-Norman BN-2 Islander|Islander]]'', landing on [[Malololailai]], Fiji, 1986]]\n'''Fiji Link''' is the trade name for '''Fiji Airlines Limited''', which is a Fijian domestic [[airline]] and a wholly owned subsidiary of the international carrier [[Fiji Airways]]. It is headquartered at the Fiji Link office in the [[Civil Aviation Authority of Fiji]] (CAAFI) compound at [[Nadi International Airport]] in [[Nadi]].<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20080323081525/http://www.pacificsun.com.fj/default.aspx?sid=PS_AboutPacificSun&pid=PS_contactInformation Contact Us].\" Fiji Airlines Limited. Retrieved on 3 October 2009. \"Fiji Airlines Limited, trading as Pacific Sun, was incorporated as a wholly owned subsidiary of Air Pacific Limited currently having its main base at the Pacific Sun office, CAAFI Compound, Nadi Airport, Fiji Islands.\" and \"Head Office Pacific Sun PO Box 9270 Nadi International Airport Fiji Islands\"</ref> It operates scheduled services to 12 destinations within the Fijian Islands as well as regionally within the [[Pacific Islands]].\n\n==History==\nDon Collingwood, a [[Aviator|pilot]] and businessman, founded what became '''Pacific Sun''' in 1980, under the name '''Sunflower Airlines''', which later changed to '''Sun Air'''. It began with a single [[Britten Norman Islander|Britten Norman BN2 Islander]] aircraft, flying the Nadi-[[Taveuni]] route. Other than the BN2 Islanders which remained the backbone of the fleet, the airline operated a wide range of [[Flat engine|piston]] and [[turboprop]] aircraft including the [[Beechcraft Baron|Beechcraft BE-95 Baron]], [[Beechcraft Queen Air|Beechcraft A65 Queen Air]], [[de Havilland Heron|de Havilland DH.114 Heron]], [[Shorts 330]], and [[De Havilland Canada DHC-6 Twin Otter|de Havilland DHC-6 Twin Otter]]. By January 2007 before official handover to Air Pacific, its fleet had grown to 12 aircraft, and the company employed nearly 140 staff.<ref>http://www.fijitv.com.fj/index.cfm?go=tv.resources&cmd=forumview&cbegin=0&uid=fijionenews&cid=11925/{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} [[Fiji Television]]</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2007, Sun Air was sold and handed over to current parent company [[Fiji Airways]], formerly Air Pacific, which had to fight off a legal challenge against the handover by the now-defunct rival domestic carrier at the time, [[Air Fiji]].<ref>http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=56250/{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''[[Fiji Times]]''</ref> Air Pacific then established the domestic airline as Fiji Airlines Limited, trading as Pacific Sun. The airline began operations with eight aircraft, including the introduction of two [[ATR 42| ATR 42\u2013500]] aircraft purchased used from [[Air Mauritius]], along with three existing BN2 Islanders and three DHC-6 Twin Otters. However, the fleet was cut back to just four between December 2010 and June 2011 due to economic cost cutting, resulting in the withdrawal of the BN2 Islander fleet as well as one DHC-6 Twin Otter.<ref name=\"airpacific1\">http://www.airpacific.com/About-Us/News/Article-ID/40c9c0e0-1418-4b52-9978-58e0f52042e5 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104064052/http://www.airpacific.com/About-Us/News/Article-ID/40c9c0e0-1418-4b52-9978-58e0f52042e5 |date=2011-01-04 }} Air Pacific</ref> Two additional leased [[De Havilland Canada DHC-6 Twin Otter|DHC-6 Twin Otters]] were added to the fleet during June 2011 to increase the Pacific Sun fleet to six aircraft.<ref>http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=173522 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913013851/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=173522 |date=2012-09-13 }} ''[[Fiji Times]]''</ref>\n\nOn 26 November 2013, parent Fiji Airways announced Pacific Sun was to be rebranded as \u2018Fiji Link\u2019. Operations as Fiji Link commenced in June 2014.<ref>http://www.fijiairways.com/experience-fiji/fiji-blog/everything-you-ever-wanted-to-know-about-the-pacific-sun-fiji-link-rebrand/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809205247/http://www.fijiairways.com/experience-fiji/fiji-blog/everything-you-ever-wanted-to-know-about-the-pacific-sun-fiji-link-rebrand/ |date=2014-08-09 }} Fijiairways.com</ref>\n\n==News==\nIn late November 2010, Pacific Sun announced that due to current economical reasons, they were withdrawing their BN2 Islander fleet from service. This meant downsizing the Pacific Sun fleet from eight aircraft to just five.<ref name=\"airpacific1\" />\n\nIn early December 2010, Pacific Sun announced the redundancy of 85 out of 210 employees. This included staff from administrative, support and operations areas as well as 15 pilots. Pacific Sun's general manager, Jim Samson, explained that continuing operating losses had resulted in management having to make some tough decisions.\n\n\"Pacific Sun has lost, on average, $6 million per year over the last three years. Continued losses are unsustainable. Regrettably as a result, we have no alternative but to restructure the airline in order to ensure its viability and success going forward,\" he said.\n\nAir Pacific chief executive officer and Pacific Sun board member David Pflieger said since Air Pacific's takeover in 2007, Pacific Sun had accumulated $18.5 million in losses. Air Pacific had loaned $44 million to purchase Sun Air's certificate and operations and two ATR-42 aircraft.<ref>http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=161908 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905091347/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=161908 |date=2012-09-05 }} ''[[Fiji Times]]''</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, Fiji Airways held a competition to rename Pacific Sun. On 13 November, the competition closed with the most votes going to Fiji Link. On 26 November, Fiji Airways released the new name. The new livery was also announced. Operations as Fiji Link commenced in June 2014.<ref>http://www.fijiairways.com/about-fiji-airways/2013-media-centre/%E2%80%98fiji-link%E2%80%99-to-take-to-the-skies-in-2014/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809205242/http://www.fijiairways.com/about-fiji-airways/2013-media-centre/%E2%80%98fiji-link%E2%80%99-to-take-to-the-skies-in-2014/ |date=2014-08-09 }} Fijiairways.com</ref>\n\n==Destinations==\nAs of August 2014, Fiji Link operates scheduled services to the following destinations 10 domestic destinations.<ref>https://twitter.com/Airlineroute/status/1191617596359004160?s=19</ref>\n\n'''Fiji'''\n*[[Cicia]] \u2013 [[Cicia Airport]]\n*[[Kadavu Island|Kadavu]] \u2013 [[Kadavu Airport]]\n*[[Labasa]] \u2013 [[Labasa Airport]]\n*[[Lakeba]] \u2013 [[Lakeba Airport]]\n*[[Nadi]] \u2013 [[Nadi International Airport]] \u2013 '''main hub'''\n*[[Rotuma]] \u2013 [[Rotuma Airport]]\n*[[Savusavu]] \u2013 [[Savusavu Airport]]\n*[[Suva]] \u2013 [[Nausori International Airport]] \u2013 '''secondary hub'''\n*[[Taveuni]] \u2013 [[Matei Airport]]\n*[[Vanua Balavu]] \u2013 [[Vanuabalavu Airport]]\n\nTerminated destinations\n'''Fiji'''\n*[[Laucala]] - [[Laucala Airport]]\n*[[Malolo Lailai]] - [[Malolo Lailai Airport]]\n*[[Mana Island (Fiji)|Mana Island]] - [[Mana Island Airport]]\n*[[Taveuni]] - [[Ura Airport]]\n*[[Yasawa-i-Rara]] - [[Yasawa Island Airport]]\n\n==Fleet==\n[[File:Sunflower Airlines logo.png|thumb|right|Logo of former Sunflower Airlines]]\nThe Fiji Link fleet consists (as of February 2020) of the following aircraft listed in the table below.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Global Airline Guide 2019 (Part One)|journal=Airliner World|issue=October 2019|page=13}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;text-align:center\"\n|- \n! rowspan=\"2\" |Aircraft\n! rowspan=\"2\" |In fleet\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Orders\n! colspan=\"3\" |Passengers\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Notes\n|- \n! <abbr title=\"Business\">J</abbr>\n! <abbr title=\"Economy\">Y</abbr>\n! Total\n|-\n|[[ATR 42|ATR 42-600]]\n|1\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|48\n|48\n|\n|-\n|[[ATR 72|ATR 72-600]]\n|2\n|&mdash;\n|4\n|64\n|68\n|\n|-\n|[[de Havilland Canada DHC-6 Twin Otter|Viking Air DHC-6-400 Twin Otter]]\n|3\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|19\n|19\n\n| \n|-\n!Total\n!7\n!0\n! colspan=\"4\" |\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category inline|Pacific Sun (airline)|Pacific Sun}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140101181914/http://www.fijiairways.com/fiji-holidays/pacific-sun/ Fiji Airways and Pacific Sun]\n{{Airlines of Fiji}}\n{{Portal bar|Aviation}}\n\n[[Category:Airlines of Fiji]]\n[[Category:Airlines established in 2006]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Oceania]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Fijian domestic airline|the international Fijian airline|Fiji Airways}}\n{{Infobox airline\n| airline        = Fiji Link\n| logo           =\n| IATA           = FJ\n| ICAO           = FJA\n| callsign       = LINK FIJI\n| founded        = 2006\n| commenced      = 2006\n| ceased         = \n| hubs           = [[Nadi International Airport]]\n| secondary_hubs = [[Nausori International Airport]]\n| focus_cities   = \n| frequent_flyer = \n| lounge         = \n| alliance       = \n| subsidiaries   = \n| fleet_size     = 7\n| destinations   = 16 (see below)\n| parent         = [[Fiji Airways]]\n| company_slogan = Best value under the Sun\n| headquarters   = [[Nadi International Airport]]<br />[[Nadi]], [[Fiji]]\n| key_people     = Shaenaz Voss (Executive General Manager)\n| website        = {{url|fijiairways.com}}\n}}\n[[File:Landing on Malololailai, Fiji, 1986 - Flickr - PhillipC.jpg|thumb|Sunflower Airlines ''[[Britten-Norman BN-2 Islander|Islander]]'', landing on [[Malololailai]], Fiji, 1986]]\n'''Fiji Link''' is the trade name for '''Fiji Airlines Limited''', which is a Fijian domestic [[airline]] and a wholly owned subsidiary of the international carrier [[Fiji Airways]]. It is headquartered at the Fiji Link office in the [[Civil Aviation Authority of Fiji]] (CAAFI) compound at [[Nadi International Airport]] in [[Nadi]].<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20080323081525/http://www.pacificsun.com.fj/default.aspx?sid=PS_AboutPacificSun&pid=PS_contactInformation Contact Us].\" Fiji Airlines Limited. Retrieved on 3 October 2009. \"Fiji Airlines Limited, trading as Pacific Sun, was incorporated as a wholly owned subsidiary of Air Pacific Limited currently having its main base at the Pacific Sun office, CAAFI Compound, Nadi Airport, Fiji Islands.\" and \"Head Office Pacific Sun PO Box 9270 Nadi International Airport Fiji Islands\"</ref> It operates scheduled services to 12 destinations within the Fijian Islands as well as regionally within the [[Pacific Islands]].\n\n==History==\nDon Collingwood, a [[Aviator|pilot]] and businessman, founded what became '''Pacific Sun''' in 1980, under the name '''Sunflower Airlines''', which later changed to '''Sun Air'''. It began with a single [[Britten Norman Islander|Britten Norman BN2 Islander]] aircraft, flying the Nadi-[[Taveuni]] route. Other than the BN2 Islanders which remained the backbone of the fleet, the airline operated a wide range of [[Flat engine|piston]] and [[turboprop]] aircraft including the [[Beechcraft Baron|Beechcraft BE-95 Baron]], [[Beechcraft Queen Air|Beechcraft A65 Queen Air]], [[de Havilland Heron|de Havilland DH.114 Heron]], [[Shorts 330]], and [[De Havilland Canada DHC-6 Twin Otter|de Havilland DHC-6 Twin Otter]]. By January 2007 before official handover to Air Pacific, its fleet had grown to 12 aircraft, and the company employed nearly 140 staff.<ref>http://www.fijitv.com.fj/index.cfm?go=tv.resources&cmd=forumview&cbegin=0&uid=fijionenews&cid=11925/{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} [[Fiji Television]]</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2007, Sun Air was sold and handed over to current parent company [[Fiji Airways]], formerly Air Pacific, which had to fight off a legal challenge against the handover by the now-defunct rival domestic carrier at the time, [[Air Fiji]].<ref>http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=56250/{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''[[Fiji Times]]''</ref> Air Pacific then established the domestic airline as Fiji Airlines Limited, trading as Pacific Sun. The airline began operations with eight aircraft, including the introduction of two [[ATR 42| ATR 42\u2013500]] aircraft purchased used from [[Air Mauritius]], along with three existing BN2 Islanders and three DHC-6 Twin Otters. However, the fleet was cut back to just four between December 2010 and June 2011 due to economic cost cutting, resulting in the withdrawal of the BN2 Islander fleet as well as one DHC-6 Twin Otter.<ref name=\"airpacific1\">http://www.airpacific.com/About-Us/News/Article-ID/40c9c0e0-1418-4b52-9978-58e0f52042e5 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104064052/http://www.airpacific.com/About-Us/News/Article-ID/40c9c0e0-1418-4b52-9978-58e0f52042e5 |date=2011-01-04 }} Air Pacific</ref> Two additional leased [[De Havilland Canada DHC-6 Twin Otter|DHC-6 Twin Otters]] were added to the fleet during June 2011 to increase the Pacific Sun fleet to six aircraft.<ref>http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=173522 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913013851/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=173522 |date=2012-09-13 }} ''[[Fiji Times]]''</ref>\n\nOn 26 November 2013, parent Fiji Airways announced Pacific Sun was to be rebranded as \u2018Fiji Link\u2019. Operations as Fiji Link commenced in June 2014.<ref>http://www.fijiairways.com/experience-fiji/fiji-blog/everything-you-ever-wanted-to-know-about-the-pacific-sun-fiji-link-rebrand/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809205247/http://www.fijiairways.com/experience-fiji/fiji-blog/everything-you-ever-wanted-to-know-about-the-pacific-sun-fiji-link-rebrand/ |date=2014-08-09 }} Fijiairways.com</ref>\n\n==News==\nIn late November 2010, Pacific Sun announced that due to current economical reasons, they were withdrawing their BN2 Islander fleet from service. This meant downsizing the Pacific Sun fleet from eight aircraft to just five.<ref name=\"airpacific1\" />\n\nIn early December 2010, Pacific Sun announced the redundancy of 85 out of 210 employees. This included staff from administrative, support and operations areas as well as 15 pilots. Pacific Sun's general manager, Jim Samson, explained that continuing operating losses had resulted in management having to make some tough decisions.\n\n\"Pacific Sun has lost, on average, $6 million per year over the last three years. Continued losses are unsustainable. Regrettably as a result, we have no alternative but to restructure the airline in order to ensure its viability and success going forward,\" he said.\n\nAir Pacific chief executive officer and Pacific Sun board member David Pflieger said since Air Pacific's takeover in 2007, Pacific Sun had accumulated $18.5 million in losses. Air Pacific had loaned $44 million to purchase Sun Air's certificate and operations and two ATR-42 aircraft.<ref>http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?