ecords|PHI|pos_c}}\n| league_place    = {{2020 OWL records|PHI|pos_l}}\n| arena           = {{ubl\n | [[The Met Philadelphia]]\n | [[Boardwalk Hall]]\n}}\n| coach           = Kim \"KDG\" Dong-gun\n| gm              = \n| owner           = [[Comcast Spectacor]]\n| playoffs        = \n| OWL allstars    = \n| earnings        = \n}}\n\nThe '''2020 Philadelphia Fusion season''' is the third season of the [[Philadelphia Fusion]]'s existence in the [[Overwatch League]] and their first under head coach Kim \"KDG\" Dong-gun. The team will look to improve upon their 15\u201313 record from 2019 and return to the playoffs after missing them the previous season. The Fusion will host three homestand weekends in the 2020 season, with the first two taking place at [[The Met Philadelphia|The Met]] in Philadelphia and the third at the [[Boardwalk Hall]] in Atlantic City.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chan |first1=Eric |title=The Fusion are bringing the Overwatch League home in 2020 with 3 homestand weekend events |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/philadelphia/fusion/fusion-are-bringing-overwatch-league-home-2020-3-homestand-weekend-events |accessdate=October 11, 2019 |work=NBC Sports Philadelphia |date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Preceding offseason ==\n=== Organizational changes ===\nIn September 2019, Director of ''Overwatch'' Operations Yann \"Kirby\" Luu, who was also the head coach of the team in 2018, left the team.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Richardson |first1=Liz |title=Shanghai Dragons, Philadelphia Fusion drop staff |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/shanghai-dragons-philadelphia-fusion-drop-staff |accessdate=October 11, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=September 23, 2019}}</ref> Less than a month later, both co-head coaches Se-hwi \"NamedHwi\" Go and Elliot \"Hayes\" Hayes announced their departures from the team.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shepard |first1=Kate |title=Philadelphia Fusion: Potential Moves for 2020 [Part II] |url=https://thegamehaus.com/overwatch/philadelphia-fusion/philadelphia-fusion-potential-moves-for-2020-part-ii/2019/10/07/ |accessdate=October 11, 2019 |work=The Game Haus |date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> The team found their replacement on October 25 with the hiring of former [[Seoul Dynasty]] head coach Kim \"KDG\" Dong-gun. Additionally, the team promoted Roston Yoo from team manager to assistant general manager the same day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Richardson |first1=Liz |title=Philadelphia Fusion hire new head coach |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/philadelphia-fusion-hire-new-head-coach |accessdate=October 26, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=October 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Roster changes ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable floatright\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align:center;\"\n|+Free agents\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Role || colspan=\"2\" | Player || rowspan=\"2\" | Contract<br>status || rowspan=\"2\" | Date signed || rowspan=\"2\" | 2020 team\n|-\n! Handle || Name\n|- style=\"background:#dfd;\"\n| [[Characters of Overwatch#Damage heroes|Damage]] || Carpe || {{sortname|Jae-Hyeok|Lee|nolink=1}} || Free agent || October 23 || Philadelphia Fusion<ref>{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Tyler |title=Philadelphia Fusion re-sign Carpe to 3-year contract extension |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/philadelphia-fusion-re-sign-carpe-to-3-year-contract-extension |accessdate=October 23, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#dfd;\"\n| [[Characters of Overwatch#Damage heroes|Damage]] || Snillo || {{sortname|Simon|Ekstr\u00f6m|nolink=1}} || Free agent || October 30 || Philadelphia Fusion<ref name=\"ESPN announcement\" />\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n|colspan=\"6\"|\n;Legend\n:{{color box|#dfd}} Re-signed/Retained by the Fusion.\n:{{color box|#fdd}} Departed from the Fusion.\n|}\n\nThe Fusion enter the new season with two free agents, four players which they have the option to retain for another year, and three players under contract.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Morello |first1=Matt |title=2020 Team Needs and Player Contract Status |url=https://overwatchleague.com/en-us/news/23178914 |accessdate=October 19, 2019 |work=Overwatch League |date=July 30, 2019}}</ref> The OWL's deadline to exercise a team option is November 11, after which any players not retained will become a free agent. Free agency officially began on October 7.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Richardson |first1=Liz |title=Overwatch League reveals player contract status for entire league |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/overwatch-league-reveals-player-contract-status-for-entire-league |accessdate=October 10, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=October 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n==== Acquisitions ====\nThe Fusion's first acquisitions of the offseason were announced on October 30. The team traded tank Shin \"BERNAR\" Se-won and support Kim \"Fuze\" Tae-hoon from [[Fusion University]] to the [[London Spitfire]] in exchange for tank Kim \"Fury\" Jun-ho, signed former [[Toronto Defiant]] DPS Lee \"Ivy\" Seung-hun, acquired support Daniel \"FunnyAstro\" Hathaway from the [[Atlanta Reign]], and promoted support Kim \"Alarm\" Kyung-bo from Fusion University. Additionally, the team announced that DPS Josue \"Eqo\" Corona as part of their roster, although he had been let go from the team earlier in the month.<ref name=\"ESPN announcement\">{{cite news |title=Fusion, Fuel, Defiant and more make Overwatch League roster moves |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/27966997/fusion-fuel-defiant-more-make-overwatch-league-roster-moves |accessdate=October 30, 2019 |work=ESPN |agency=Reuters |date=October 30, 2019}}</ref> On November 25, the team announced that they had acquired DPS Jeong \"Heesu\" Hee-su from [[RunAway]], although he would not turn 18, and thus inelegible to play, until late March.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peres |first1=Pedro |title=Philadelphia Fusion sign Heesu |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/philadelphia-fusion-sign-heesu |accessdate=November 27, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=November 25, 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn November 26, the acquisition of DPS Philip \"ChipSa\" Graham, a popular streamer, was announced.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Richardson |first1=Liz |title=Philadelphia Fusion sign ChipSa |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/philadelphia-fusion-sign-chipsa |accessdate=November 27, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=November 26, 2019}}</ref> This signing proved to be controversial, as several figures in the professional ''Overwatch'' community criticized the signing. Namely, [[Envy Gaming]] content creator Justin \"Jayne\" Conroy noted his lack of professional experience and accused the Fusion of [[nepotism]], as ChipSa's brother Chris \"ChrisTFer\" Graham works as an assistant coach for the team.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gwilliam |first1=Michael |title=Jayne says Fusion \"spat in pros' faces\" by signing Overwatch streamer |url=https://www.dexerto.com/overwatch/jayne-says-fusion-spat-in-pros-faces-signing-overwatch-streamer-1292095 |accessdate=November 27, 2019 |work=Dexerto.com |date=November 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Departures ====\nThe Fusion's first free agent to depart from the team was support Alberto \"neptuNo\" Gonz\u00e1lez, who had been with the team since its inception in 2017, as the team announced that they had parted ways with him on October 21.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shepard |first1=Kate |title=The Philadelphia Fusion Release Neptuno |url=https://thegamehaus.com/overwatch/the-philadelphia-fusion-release-neptuno/2019/10/21/ |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |work=The Game Haus |date=October 21, 2019}}</ref> The following day, the team elected not to exercise their option to retain DPS Josue \"Eqo\" Corona, who was also a inaugural season team member.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Samples |first1=Rachel |title=Philadelphia Fusion part ways with Eqo ahead of 2020 Overwatch League season |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/philadelphia-fusion-part-ways-with-eqo-ahead-of-2020-overwatch-league-season |accessdate=October 23, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Support Elijah \"Elk\" Gallagher and DPS Finley \"Kyb\" Adisi, the final two players that were under team options, were released a day later.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Samples |first1=Rachel |title=Philadelphia Fusion release Elk and KYB |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/philadelphia-fusion-release-elk-and-kyb |accessdate=October 23, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> Although he was announced as a part of the Fusion's roster in October, DPS Simon \"Snillo\" Ekstr\u00f6m was released from the team on December 19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Richardson |first1=Liz |title=Philadelphia Fusion part ways with Snillo |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/philadelphia-fusion-part-ways-with-snillo |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Roster ==\n{{Philadelphia Fusion roster}}\n\n== Standings ==\n{{2020 Overwatch League standings}}\n\n== Game log ==\n{{OWL game log start|Philadelphia Fusion|2020|wins=5|losses=1}}\n\n{{OWL game log section|Philadelphia Fusion|February\u2013March: 5\u20131|hide=y|\n{{Overwatch collapsible box\n| match = 1  | date = February 15 | year = 2020 | time = {{24 h to 12 h|18:00}} [[Eastern Standard Time (North America)|EST]]\n| team1 = Washington Justice  | team1score = 1\n| team2 = Philadelphia Fusion  | team2score = 3\n| map1 = Nepal | map1team1score = 1 | map1team2score = 2\n| map2 = Havana | map2team1score = 2 | map2team2score = 1\n| map3 = King's Row | map3team1score = 2 | map3team2score = 3\n| map4 = Temple of Anubis | map4team1score = 1 | map4team2score = 3\n| location = [[Philadelphia, PA]] | stadium = [[The Met Philadelphia]] | host = Philadelphia Fusion\n}}\n{{Overwatch collapsible box\n| match = 2  | date = February 16 | year = 2020 | time = {{24 h to 12 h|18:00}} [[Eastern Standard Time (North America)|EST]]\n| team1 = Florida Mayhem  | team1score = 0\n| team2 = Philadelphia Fusion | tea