 {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: William Packer, Untitled\n* Arcs + Surfaces, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}} (exhibition catalogue). Texts: Angela Kingston, New Paintings by Eric Butcher, Catherine Shearn, A Conversation with Eric Butcher.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ericbutcher.com Eric Butcher website]\n*[http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ Eric Butcher at Toomey Tourell gallery]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher Eric Butcher at Galerie Robert Drees]\n*[https://www.patrickheide.com/artists/eric-butcher Eric Butcher at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butcher, Eric}}\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century English painters]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singaporean emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People associated with Arts University Bournemouth]]\n", "text_old": "'''Eric Butcher''' (born 1970) is an English painter.\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Life and work==\nEric Butcher was born in Singapore in 1970. He read philosophy at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], graduating in 1994 and in 2001 he completed an MA in Fine Art at [[Wimbledon College of Art|Wimbledon School of Art]]. He has exhibited extensively in the UK and internationally with shows in Germany, Italy, Australia and the USA.<ref name=\"Underground\">(2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.78. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> He currently shows with Toomey Tourell gallery, San Francisco<ref>Toomey-Tourell Fine Art [http://toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ \"Eric Butcher\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001153714/http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher |date=2012-10-01 }}</ref> and Galerie Robert Drees in Hannover.<ref>Galerie Robert Drees [http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher |date=2012-08-23 }}\"Eric Butcher\"</ref> He has received awards from the [[Arts Council England|Arts Council, England]] and the [[Arts and Humanities Research Council]]. He has also held an Arts Institute at Bournemouth Research Fellowship (now the [[Arts University Bournemouth|AUB]]<ref>[http://aub.ac.uk/about-us/governance/\u201dArts University College Bournemouth\u201d]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref>) and was the Centre for Arts International Research/Liverpool School of Art & Design Multiple Perspectives Fellow 2007.<ref name=\"Underground\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, ER.358.jpg|thumb|left|alt=ER.358.|ER.358 Oil and resin on extruded aluminium box sections.]]\nButcher's earliest exhibited works were compositions of oil, resin and spray paint on large, tablet-like MDF supports. The combination of painted surface and exaggerated depth of the support made the works deliberately and obviously three-dimensional objects \u2013 an \u2018attempt to deny the viewer the desire to see the surface as anything other than surface\u2019.<ref>(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.11. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> This composed physical presence was inherent in even the most restrained of Butcher's works, as William Packer would go on to say in his introduction to Butcher's 2005 catalogue, Carbon Candy, \u2018even when hung conventionally, flat to the wall, they remain obviously and directly physical\u2019.<ref>\u201dCarbon Candy\u201d, p.4. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}}.</ref> Although characterised by their appearance \u2013 an abstract \u2018accretion of paint, resin and various other fluids\u2019<ref name=\"Arcs\">(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.12. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> - their manufacture was faithful to the rules that govern Butcher's creative process.<ref>Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/about/statement/ \"statement\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/about/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> Butcher has said of his practice that \u2018the application or subtraction of paint as a set of processes is achieved through a variety of continually evolving techniques which draw attention to the physical properties of my materials\u2019,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\">Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/about/statement/\"statement\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/about/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> a result that would be most clearly manifest in his subsequent metal works. The introduction of metal as a support revolutionised Butcher's creative output and his approach to the act of painting, \u2018it may just be a flat piece of metal\u2026 But they all have little nicks, edges and imperfections\u2026 the end result is an accumulation of what I have learnt about that surface\u2019.<ref name=\"Arcs\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, GR.578.jpg|thumb|right|alt=GR.578.|GR.578 Blind embossed paper with cutouts.]]\n\u2018The application or subtraction of paint\u2019 in Butcher's practice is executed through the use of \u2018a metal blade drawn across the painting\u2019s surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\">\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.7. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> pulling a thin transparent monochrome of oil and resin over the metal support, \u2018this procedure is then repeated and repeated, building up a surface of accumulated residues'.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> The outcome of each painting is determined by \u2018variations in colour modulation\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> and largely \u2018by the physical characteristics of the support\u2019.<ref>Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.co.uk\u201dstatement\u201d]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref> Paint is registered in vertical and horizontal bands across the surface of the metal plane, with areas of metal left unpainted and its polished face exposed to the viewer. Although Butcher has a uniform approach to each work,<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> they nevertheless differ vastly from one another as the artist may encounter subtle material differences in the surface of each extrusion; burrs in the metal itself or unexpected variations in the applied paint wash.<ref>Sheldon, Julie (2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.32. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> Almost every piece will seek to preserve some element of the metal as well, \u2018the aluminium asserts itself as the artwork\u2019s true substance\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> As Butcher seeks to articulate the surfaces of aluminium structures,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> he does so not only through the repetitive layers of colour application, but also through the preservation of the support's original condition (before his intervention) \u2013 both make for an overall representation of that particular structure's history.\n\nFor the Material Witness exhibition at Toomey Tourell gallery in 2010, Butcher exhibited fourteen of his painted aluminium extrusions.<ref name=\"Baker\">Baker, Kenneth (March 13, 2010). \u201cButcher Shines at Toomey Tourell\u201d. San Francisco Chronicle, p.E-1.</ref> Hung vertically and spaced asymmetrically with a measured and careful distance between one another,<ref name=\"Baker\" /> the display articulated Butcher's increasing awareness of, and preoccupation with, \u2018installation\u2019 in creating a total cohesive experience rather than an isolated object.<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> As Kenneth Baker, in his [[San Francisco Chronicle]] review, wrote of the work's interaction with the space it occupied, \u2018to walk this piece is to compose and recompose it through observation. Its geometry and built-in illusionism dictate that it cannot be seen whole\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> This can also be said of Butcher's curatorial practice, where, as in the Definite Article exhibition curated by the artist himself,<ref>\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.3. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> he deals with the scale and arrangement of works by Roger Ackling, [[Marc Vaux]] and Cathy Wade, as well as his own. Butcher's attempts within his own works in that exhibition to, \u2018engage the space around the painted surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> were similarly factors that he encountered in his curation of the exhibition as a whole, \u2018each of the artists\u2026 employs a range of techniques to encourage the viewer to engage with the work physically\u2019.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" />\n\nAs a consequence of this preoccupation with installation, some of Butcher's most recent pieces, his works on paper, experiment diagrammatically with possible arrangements for his large-scale installations of aluminium pieces, introducing elements of chance.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\">\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 77. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> In these paper works, impressions of metal plates are embossed into sheets of saturated paper by running it through a printing press.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 80. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> Some sections of the plates\u2019 impressions are then highlighted by ink, whereas some sections are cut out altogether \u2013 some left purely as a trace.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\" /> Butcher refers to this register of trace in his paper works as speaking, metaphorically, of loss and absence.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 81. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n*Butcher Shines at Toomey Tourell, Kenneth Baker, San Francisco Chronicle, pg. E - 1, March 13, 2010\n* Material Witness, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}. Text: Roy Exley, Eric Butcher & the Aluminium Works\n* Underground, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}. Texts: John Haldane, Underground; Lee Trimings, Loveslaves; Julie Sheldon, Process by Protocol; Tania Kovats, Digging.\n* Meeting Place, the Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum, Bournemouth, in association with Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, {{ISBN|978-0-901196-20-0}}, Ed. Stephanie James & Les Buckingham. Texts inc. Eric Butcher, Discoveries\n* Art at More London, The LG collection of Contemporary art, London (collection catalogue), Ed. Margaret O\u2019Regan\n* Hanging Garden, Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, Bournemouth {{ISBN|0-901196-09-6}} (exhibition catalogue). Text, James Barron, Spaces, In, Out and Around\n* Definite Article, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: Eric Butcher, Objects and Surfaces. Essay reprinted (abridged) in Art & Architecture Journal, No. 63, Autumn 2005\n* Carbon Candy, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: William Packer, Untitled\n* Arcs + Surfaces, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}} (exhibition catalogue). Texts: Angela Kingston, New Paintings by Eric Butcher, Catherine Shearn, A Conversation with Eric Butcher.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ericbutcher.com Eric Butcher website]\n*[http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ Eric Butcher at Toomey Tourell gallery]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher Eric Butcher at Galerie Robert Drees]\n*[https://www.patrickheide.com/artists/eric-butcher Eric Butcher at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butcher, Eric}}\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century English painters]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singaporean emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People associated with Arts University Bournemouth]]\n", "name_user": "Barrettjonathan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Exhibitions history box with selected solo exhibitions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Butcher"}
{"title_page": "Offensive coordinator", "text_new": "{{short description|Coach responsible for the offense on a gridiron football team}}\nAn '''offensive coordinator''' is a member of the coaching staff of an [[American football]] or [[Canadian football]] team who is in charge of the team's [[offense (sports)|offense]].  Generally, along with the [[defensive coordinator]], he represents the second level of command structure after the [[head coach]].  The offensive coordinator is in charge of the team's offensive game plan, and typically calls offensive plays during the game, although some offensive-minded head coaches also handle play-calling.<ref name=dummies>\"[http://www.dummies.com/how-to/content/the-coaching-staff-in-american-football.html The Coaching Staff in American Football],\" Dummies.com.  Retrieved October 6, 2014.</ref>  Several position coaches work under the coordinator (position groupings can include [[quarterback]]s, [[wide receiver]]s, [[offensive line]], [[running back]]s, and [[tight end]]s).  The coordinator may also coach a position (typically quarterbacks).<ref name=dummies />\n\nUnlike most position coaches in football, who are usually on the sidelines during games, offensive coordinators have the option of operating from the [[press box]] instead of being on the sideline.  There are advantages and disadvantages to both locations.\n\nSince 2009, nearly 40% of head coaches hired in the NFL had been serving as offensive coordinators.<ref>[https://www.axios.com/nfl-rooney-rule-head-coach-diversity-bdf6228d-0b29-4cdd-bb95-b6d7cdb87b9e.html]</ref>\n\n==How to Become Offensive Coordinator==\n\n===Essentials Information===\nIf you want to become a highschool, college, or NFL coach, here are some essential steps to take you down that path. Having a passion for the sport and training athletes will be very important if this is a targeted career path. Have knowledge of the game, it's important to develop your skills of the game and get up-to-date information <ref>Study.com. (2019, November 25). How to Become A Football Coach: Education and Career Roadmap. Retrieved April 10, 2020, from https://study.com/articles/How_to_Become_a_Football_Coach_Education_and_Career_Roadmap.html</ref>  Volunteering at a local high school or team can help get the experience and knowlesge needed to more up the ladder. Be open to helping at any position and than time, establish your goals with the coaches and start specailizing your skills with the offensive players. Establishing time with a team is very important as well. It may take a few seasons before getting promoted into any coaching position in any level. \n===How to Become a High School Offensive Coordinator===\nIf you're looking to stay in the high school level, be open into becoming a teacher or an administrator. <ref>Study.com. (2019, November 25). How to Become A Football Coach: Education and Career Roadmap. Retrieved April 10, 2020, from https://study.com/articles/How_to_Become_a_Football_Coach_Education_and_Career_Roadmap.html</ref>This is why volunteering is important too. After volunteering with a school, you can see what positions are available within the school and what coaches are needed for school. Since your goal is offensive coordinator, you'll be searching for opening for coaching positions related to offensive positions. Pursueing coaching-realated certifications will be very beneficial<ref>Study.com. (2019, November 25). How to Become A Football Coach: Education and Career Roadmap. Retrieved April 10, 2020, from https://study.com/articles/How_to_Become_a_Football_Coach_Education_and_Career_Roadmap.html</ref>. It will increase your knowledge and be a highlight on your resume. \nTaking these instructions will help assist you into getting the offensive coaching posiiton with a high school team. Next step is to stay a few seasons in an offensive coaching position, learn what each offensive coach handles, and after a few seasons you'll apply for the Offensive Coordinator position. \n\n===How to become an College Offensive Coordinator===\nAfter following the procedures above, you'll have a good start moving your way into the collegiate level<ref>Study.com. (2019, November 25). How to Become A Football Coach: Education and Career Roadmap. Retrieved April 10, 2020, from https://study.com/articles/How_to_Become_a_Football_Coach_Education_and_Career_Roadmap.html</ref>. Prior coaching experience is very obviously very important and it's better if you lead some sucessful teams. Establashing yourself for a college offensive coordinator positon will require experience coaching the offensive players at teh collegiate level. Assisting a few seasons as an offensive coach, sucessfully, will help lead your way into any offensive coordinating positions. \n\n===NFL Offensive Coordinator===\nNow leading into the NFL Offesenive Coordinator. This requires a years of coaching experience at collegiatly and professionally. Majority of these years will have to be sucessful to be highly considered for the position. Starting out in the NFL coaching, you'll start coaching/assisting the offensive teams and move up through the hierarchy. Be ready to make professional coaching your main priority too. According to the Baltimore Ravens John Harbaugh, him and other NFL coaches spend 168 hours a week <ref>Valkenburg, K. V. (2013, November 22). A week in the life of a coach. Retrieved April 7, 2020, from https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/10012376/baltimore-ravens-head-coach-john-harbaugh-clocks-long-hours-prep-game-day-espn-magazine\n</ref>. Yes he is the head coach but offensive and defensive coordinators will put in similar hours at the head coach. \n\n==Common Offensive Coordinator's Stategies==\nEvery Offensive Coordinator has their own coaching philosophies for their offense, however many of them stem from similar and basic ideas. Coaches are always learning and developing new techniques. A basic rule that seems like commmon sense would be minimizing mistakes. The best way for that is, Turnovers and penalties are avoidable through sound practices and preparation\" (Hutchison, 2008).  Another common ideaology for offensive coordinators is to dominate the defense. A strong offense will break the other team's denfese physcially and mentally <ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |title=10 Golden Rules of Offensive Football |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Offensive_coordinator&action=edit&section=6 |website=Active |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> Next is to make sure the defense never crowds the line of scrimamge <ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |title=10 Golden Rules of Offensive Football |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Offensive_coordinator&action=edit&section=6 |website=Active |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> It brings the offensive to a total disadvange with running plays and pursusing the field. Another common style is the Air Coryell system. This initiates lots of deep routes from the outside receivers, timing routes, and having the quarterback throw to \"a spot,\" on the field <ref>{{cite web |title=The Main 5 Offensive Systems in the NFL |url=https://hydeandzeke.com/every-nfl-team-offensive-tendencies/ |website=Hyde & Zeke Champion |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>. Following that is the Spread offense which spreads the defense out<ref>{{cite web |title=The Main 5 Offensive Systems in the NFL |url=https://hydeandzeke.com/every-nfl-team-offensive-tendencies/ |website=Hyde & Zeke Champion |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>. The West Coast Offense will , \"Focuses mainly on zone blocking runs and quick timing passes\" (Marchant, 2019). While streching the other teams defense horizontally, the offense wil utilize short passes and the run game.  The Erhardt-Perkins Offense is a good example of a combination of techniques. It's important to remember to adapt new staregies and modify them so they fit your philosophy. Leaning will be a continues contribution you [the offensive coordinator] will have to take take to improve your team. The Erhardt-Perkins Offensve takes out the lengthy play-calls in the previous plays mentioned, Air-Coryell and West Coast Offense, and uses one-or-two word names as a given concept for passing plays <ref>{{cite web |title=The Main 5 Offensive Systems in the NFL |url=https://hydeandzeke.com/every-nfl-team-offensive-tendencies/ |website=Hyde & Zeke Champion |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>. Next common system is the Air Raid Offense which includes two wides outs and 2 slot receivers to attack one sides of the field, leaving one receiver on the opposite side of the field <ref>{{cite web |title=The Main 5 Offensive Systems in the NFL |url=https://hydeandzeke.com/every-nfl-team-offensive-tendencies/ |website=Hyde & Zeke Champion |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of active National Football League offensive coordinators]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{NFL offensive coordinator navbox}}\n\n[[Category:American football occupations]]\n[[Category:Coaches of American football|*Offensive coordinator]]\n\n\n{{Americanfootball-stub}}\n{{Canadianfootball-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Coach responsible for the offense on a gridiron football team}}\nAn '''offensive coordinator''' is a member of the coaching staff of an [[American football]] or [[Canadian football]] team who is in charge of the team's [[offense (sports)|offense]].  Generally, along with the [[defensive coordinator]], he represents the second level of command structure after the [[head coach]].  The offensive coordinator is in charge of the team's offensive game plan, and typically calls offensive plays during the game, although some offensive-minded head coaches also handle play-calling.<ref name=dummies>\"[http://www.dummies.com/how-to/content/the-coaching-staff-in-american-football.html The Coaching Staff in American Football],\" Dummies.com.  Retrieved October 6, 2014.</ref>  Several position coaches work under the coordinator (position groupings can include [[quarterback]]s, [[wide receiver]]s, [[offensive line]], [[running back]]s, and [[tight end]]s).  The coordinator may also coach a position (typically quarterbacks).<ref name=dummies />\n\nUnlike most position coaches in football, who are usually on the sidelines during games, offensive coordinators have the option of operating from the [[press box]] instead of being on the sideline.  There are advantages and disadvantages to both locations.\n\nSince 2009, nearly 40% of head coaches hired in the NFL had been serving as offensive coordinators.<ref>[https://www.axios.com/nfl-rooney-rule-head-coach-diversity-bdf6228d-0b29-4cdd-bb95-b6d7cdb87b9e.html]</ref>\n\n==How to Become Offensive Coordinator==\n\n===Essentials Information===\nIf you want to become a highschool, college, or NFL coach, here are some essential steps to take you down that path. Having a passion for the sport and training athletes will be very important if this is a targeted career path. Have knowledge of the game, it's important to develop your skills of the game and get up-to-date information <ref>Study.com. (2019, November 25). How to Become A Football Coach: Education and Career Roadmap. Retrieved April 10, 2020, from https://study.com/articles/How_to_Become_a_Football_Coach_Education_and_Career_Roadmap.html</ref>  Volunteering at a local high school or team can help get the experience and knowlesge needed to more up the ladder. Be open to helping at any position and than time, establish your goals with the coaches and start specailizing your skills with the offensive players. Establishing time with a team is very important as well. It may take a few seasons before getting promoted into any coaching position in any level. \n===How to Become a High School Offensive Coordinator===\nIf you're looking to stay in the high school level, be open into becoming a teacher or an administrator. <ref>Study.com. (2019, November 25). How to Become A Football Coach: Education and Career Roadmap. Retrieved April 10, 2020, from https://study.com/articles/How_to_Become_a_Football_Coach_Education_and_Career_Roadmap.html</ref>This is why volunteering is important too. After volunteering with a school, you can see what positions are available within the school and what coaches are needed for school. Since your goal is offensive coordinator, you'll be searching for opening for coaching positions related to offensive positions. Pursueing coaching-realated certifications will be very beneficial<ref>Study.com. (2019, November 25). How to Become A Football Coach: Education and Career Roadmap. Retrieved April 10, 2020, from https://study.com/articles/How_to_Become_a_Football_Coach_Education_and_Career_Roadmap.html</ref>. It will increase your knowledge and be a highlight on your resume. \nTaking these instructions will help assist you into getting the offensive coaching posiiton with a high school team. Next step is to stay a few seasons in an offensive coaching position, learn what each offensive coach handles, and after a few seasons you'll apply for the Offensive Coordinator position. \n\n===How to become an College Offensive Coordinator===\nAfter following the procedures above, you'll have a good start moving your way into the collegiate level<ref>Study.com. (2019, November 25). How to Become A Football Coach: Education and Career Roadmap. Retrieved April 10, 2020, from https://study.com/articles/How_to_Become_a_Football_Coach_Education_and_Career_Roadmap.html</ref>. Prior coaching experience is very obviously very important and it's better if you lead some sucessful teams. Establashing yourself for a college offensive coordinator positon will require experience coaching the offensive players at teh collegiate level. Assisting a few seasons as an offensive coach, sucessfully, will help lead your way into any offensive coordinating positions. \n\n===NFL Offensive Coordinator===\nNow leading into the NFL Offesenive Coordinator. This requires a years of coaching experience at collegiatly and professionally. Majority of these years will have to be sucessful to be highly considered for the position. Starting out in the NFL coaching, you'll start coaching/assisting the offensive teams and move up through the hierarchy. Be ready to make professional coaching your main priority too. According to the Baltimore Ravens John Harbaugh, him and other NFL coaches spend 168 hours a week <ref>Valkenburg, K. V. (2013, November 22). A week in the life of a coach. Retrieved April 7, 2020, from https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/10012376/baltimore-ravens-head-coach-john-harbaugh-clocks-long-hours-prep-game-day-espn-magazine\n</ref>. Yes he is the head coach but offensive and defensive coordinators will put in similar hours at the head coach. \n\n==Common Offensive Coordinator's Stategies==\nEvery Offensive Coordinator has their own coaching philosophies for their offense, however many of them stem from similar and basic ideas. Coaches are always learning and developing new techniques. A basic rule that seems like commmon sense would be minimizing mistakes. The best way for that is, Turnovers and penalties are avoidable through sound practices and preparation\" (Hutchison, 2008).  Another common ideaology for offensive coordinators is to dominate the defense. A strong offense will break the other team's denfese physcially and mentally <ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |title=10 Golden Rules of Offensive Football |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Offensive_coordinator&action=edit&section=6 |website=Active |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> Next is to make sure the defense never crowds the line of scrimamge <ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |title=10 Golden Rules of Offensive Football |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Offensive_coordinator&action=edit&section=6 |website=Active |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> It brings the offensive to a total disadvange with running plays and pursusing the field. Another common style is the Air Coryell system. This initiates lots of deep routes from the outside receivers, timing routes, and having the quarterback throw to \"a spot,\" on the field <ref>{{cite web |title=The Main 5 Offensive Systems in the NFL |url=https://hydeandzeke.com/every-nfl-team-offensive-tendencies/ |website=Hyde & Zeke Champion |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>. Following that is the Spread offense which spreads the defense out<ref>{{cite web |title=The Main 5 Offensive Systems in the NFL |url=https://hydeandzeke.com/every-nfl-team-offensive-tendencies/ |website=Hyde & Zeke Champion |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>. The West Coast Offense will , \"Focuses mainly on zone blocking runs and quick timing passes\" (Marchant, 2019). While streching the other teams defense horizontally, the offense wil utilize short passes and the run game.  The Erhardt-Perkins Offense is a good example of a combination of techniques. It's important to remember to adapt new staregies and modify them so they fit your philosophy. Leaning will be a continues contribution you [the offensive coordinator] will have to take take to improve your team. The Erhardt-Perkins Offensve takes out the lengthy play-calls in the previous plays mentioned, Air-Coryell and West Coast Offense, and uses one-or-two word names as a given concept for passing plays <ref>{{cite web |title=The Main 5 Offensive Systems in the NFL |url=https://hydeandzeke.com/every-nfl-team-offensive-tendencies/ |website=Hyde & Zeke Champion |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>. Next common system is the Air Raid Offense which includes two wides outs and 2 slot recievers to attack one sides of the field, leaving one receiver on the opposite side of the field <ref>{{cite web |title=The Main 5 Offensive Systems in the NFL |url=https://hydeandzeke.com/every-nfl-team-offensive-tendencies/ |website=Hyde & Zeke Champion |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of active National Football League offensive coordinators]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{NFL offensive coordinator navbox}}\n\n[[Category:American football occupations]]\n[[Category:Coaches of American football|*Offensive coordinator]]\n\n\n{{Americanfootball-stub}}\n{{Canadianfootball-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "reciever > receiver", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Offensive_coordinator"}
{"title_page": "Alberto Malesani", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{lead too short|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Alberto Malesani\n| image = Malesani2010.jpg\n| caption = Malesani with [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] in 2010\n| fullname = Alberto Malesani\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1954|6|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Verona]], Italy\n| currentclub = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| height = 1.79m\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = Audace S. Michele\n| youthyears2 = 1970 | youthclubs2 = [[Vicenza Calcio|Vicenza]]\n| years1 = | clubs1 = Audace S. Michele | caps1 = | goals1 = \n| manageryears1 = 1987\u20131990 | managerclubs1 = [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]] (junior)\n| manageryears2 = 1990\u20131991 | managerclubs2 = Chievo (youth)\n| manageryears3 = 1991\u20131993 | managerclubs3 = Chievo (assistant)\n| manageryears4 = 1993\u20131997 | managerclubs4 = Chievo\n| manageryears5 = 1997\u20131998 | managerclubs5 = [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]\n| manageryears6 = 1998\u20132001 | managerclubs6 = [[Parma F.C.|Parma]]\n| manageryears7 = 2001\u20132003 | managerclubs7 = [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]]\n| manageryears8 = 2003\u20132004 | managerclubs8 = [[Modena F.C.|Modena]]\n| manageryears9 = 2005\u20132006 | managerclubs9 = [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]]\n| manageryears10 = 2007     | managerclubs10 = [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]]\n| manageryears11 = 2007\u20132008| managerclubs11 = [[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]]\n| manageryears12 = 2009\u20132010| managerclubs12 = [[A.C. Siena|Siena]]\n| manageryears13 = 2010\u20132011| managerclubs13 = [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]]\n| manageryears14 = 2011     | managerclubs14 = [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]]\n| manageryears15 = 2012     | managerclubs15 = Genoa\n| manageryears16 = 2013     | managerclubs16 = [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]]\n| manageryears17 = 2014     | managerclubs17 = [[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]]\n}}\n'''Alberto Malesani''' ({{IPA-it|al\u02c8b\u025brto male\u02c8za\u02d0ni}}; born 5 June 1954) is an Italian [[association football]] [[Association football manager|manager]] and former [[Association football|footballer]]. As a manager, he is mostly remembered for his successful spell with [[Parma F.C.|Parma]] during the late 90s, where he won the [[Coppa Italia]], the [[UEFA Cup]], and the [[Supercoppa Italiana]].\n\n==Career==\n===Early career and breakthrough at Chievo===\n[[Image:Malesani.jpg|thumb|A young Malesani during his first stint as Chievo head coach]]\nMalesani career as player was mostly spent on a [[Verona|Veronese]] amateur team Audace S. Michele, where he obtained a promotion from [[Serie D]] to [[Serie C]] in 1976\u201377, appearing fourteen times on that season.<ref>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.hellastory.net/pages/scheda.cfm?id=7D590D79-4854-12EA-BD663F99594DEB70 HELLASTORY.net | La Scheda di Alberto Malesani<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He retired from playing football at the age of 24, and worked at [[Canon (company)|Canon]] in [[Amsterdam]], where he studied the [[Ajax Amsterdam]] [[total football]] training methods.<ref>[http://www.tifonet.it/fiore/malesani/bio.htm Alberto Malesani \u2013 l'antipersonaggio (la biografia)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> His passion for coaching was so great, that on his honeymoon, he decided to go to [[Barcelona]] in order to watch [[Johan Cruijff]]'s coaching sessions at [[Barcelona FC]].\n \nMalesani left his job at Canon in 1990 order to pursue a coaching career at [[Serie C1]] team [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]] for the ''Allievi'' youth squad. In 1991, he is assistant of head coach [[Carlo De Angelis]] in the first team, and in 1993 he becomes head coach himself. His first season as head coach ended in a historical promotion to [[Serie B]] for then-unknown Chievo.\n\n===Fiorentina, Parma and UEFA Cup triumph===\nMalesani left Chievo in 1997, after three impressive Serie B seasons and a narrowly missed promotion in the Serie A league in order to become [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]'s boss, in what was his first stint in the Italian top flight.\n\nA good Fiorentina season convinced [[Parma F.C.|Parma]] to appoint Malesani as new head coach in 1998, where he won a [[Coppa Italia]], a [[UEFA Cup]], an [[Italian Super Cup]] and obtained two fourth places before being sacked during the [[2000\u201301 Serie A|2000\u201301 season]].<ref name=auction>{{cite web|url=http://gazzettaworld.gazzetta.it/off-the-ball/malesani-bid-uefa-cup-parma/?refresh_ce-cp|title=Malesani bids for UEFA Cup in Parma auction|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Sumeet Paul|date=7 October 2015|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/63457/when-parma-ruled-europe|title=When Parma ruled Europe|publisher=Football Italia|author1=Dave Taylor|date=5 March 2015|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===From Verona to Panathinaikos and Udinese===\nAfter losing his job at Parma, Malesani then coached [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hellasverona.it/news.php?id=473|title=E' UFFICIALE, ALBERTO MALESANI SARA' L'ALLENATORE DELL'HELLAS VERONA ANCHE NELLA STAGIONE 2002/2003|date=8 February 2002|accessdate=25 April 2014|publisher=Hellas Verona FC|language=Italian}}</ref> and [[Modena F.C.|Modena]], failing to save the clubs from relegation in both cases; successively he moved abroad to coach [[Greece|Greek]] side [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]]. Panathinaikos remains the club with the highest percentage of wins in Malesani's career to date (60%).\n\nMalesani was appointed coach of [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] in January 2007, as replacement for [[Giovanni Galeone]]. He led his side to a not particularly impressive tenth place in the [[2006\u201307 Serie A]] final table, only seven points far from relegation, being not confirmed for the following season. On 27 November 2007 he was unveiled as [[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]]'s new head coach, replacing [[Luigi Cagni]].<ref name=\"cagni_sacked\">{{cite news|url=http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/nov26p.html |date=26 November 2007 |accessdate=27 November 2007 |publisher=Football Italia |title=Empoli axe Cagni |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071128121509/http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/nov26p.html |archivedate=28 November 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was axed on 31 March 2008 following a 2\u20130 home defeat to [[U.C. Sampdoria]] which left Empoli down in last place in the league table.<ref name=\"malesani_sacked\">{{cite news |title=L'Empoli licenzia Malesani. In panchina torna Cagni|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Empoli/Primo_Piano/2008/03_Marzo/31/malesani.shtml |publisher= La Gazzetta dello Sport |date= 31 March 2008 |accessdate=31 March 2008 |language=Italian}}</ref>\n\n===From Siena to Bologna===\nOn 23 November 2009, he was appointed as the new head coach of [[A.C. Siena|Siena]], replacing [[Marco Baroni]].<ref name=\"malesani_siena\">{{cite news |url=http://www.acsiena.it/comunicatidetail.php3?id=8099|language=Italian |publisher=AC Siena |accessdate=23 November 2009 |date=23 November 2009 |title=Raggiunto l'accordo con Alberto Malesani}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> On 21 May 2010, was released by Siena.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acsiena.it/dettaglionews_3.php?id=8433|title=SportReggio {{!}} Recensioni, Prezzi, Classifiche e News|website=SportReggio|language=it-IT|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 September 2010, he signed a one-year contract for [[Bologna F.C.|Bologna]].<ref>[https://archive.is/20100905064049/http://www.bolognafc.it/it/news/pagine/9274/Malesani-%E2%80%9CFinalmente-sulla-panchina-del-Bologna%E2%80%9D.html Malesani: \u201cFinalmente sulla panchina del Bologna\u201d]</ref>\nAfter a successful season which saw his club finish in 16th place, six points clear of relegation, despite a three-point deduction for tax problems and running feuds over the club's ownership, Malesani was replaced by [[Pierpaolo Bisoli]] on 26 May 2011.<ref>[http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/26052011/58/serie-bologna-dump-malesani-bisoli.html Serie A - Bologna dump Malesani for Bisoli]</ref>\n\n===Genoa===\nOn 19 June 2011, [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]] officially announced that Malesani would be the new first team head coach.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.genoacfc.it/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=12228&Itemid=31|title=ALBERTO MALESANI NUOVO ALLENATORE |date=19 June 2011|accessdate=19 June 2011|publisher=Genoa C.F.C. |language=Italian}}</ref> However, after Genoa was defeated 6-1 by Napoli, Malesani was fired.<ref>[http://www.chron.com/sports/article/Genoa-fires-coach-Malesani-hires-Marino-2420033.php]</ref> He returned to Genoa on 2 April 2012, taking over from [[Pasquale Marino]] who had previously replaced him only to be sacked a few months later.<ref name=\"malesani_back\">{{cite news|url=http://www.genoacfc.it/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14199&Itemid=31 |title=COMUNICATO STAMPA |date=2 April 2012|accessdate=3 April 2012|work=Genoa CFC}}</ref> His second stint as Genoa boss lasted however only twenty days, as he was sacked once again on 22 April after a 1\u20134 home loss to [[A.C. Siena|Siena]] that left Genoa one point shy of relegation, and led to massive protests from Genoa fans during the game.<ref name=\"decanio_genoa\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cittadigenova.com/Genova/Sport/Incubo-Genoa-Malesani-nuovamente-50639.aspx |title=Incubo Genoa/ Malesani nuovamente esonerato. Squadra a Gigi De Canio |date=22 April 2012 |accessdate=22 April 2012 |work=Citt\u00e0 di Genova |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407083252/http://www.cittadigenova.com/Genova/Sport/Incubo-Genoa-Malesani-nuovamente-50639.aspx |archivedate=7 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Palermo===\nOn 5 February 2013, Malesani was appointed as the manager of [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://football-italia.net/30395/official-malesani-joins-palermo|title=Official: Malesani joins Palermo {{!}} Football Italia|website=football-italia.net|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHowever, after three matches in charge, on 24 February 2013 Malesani was relieved from his duties as the manager.<ref name=\"malesani-sacked-palermo\">{{cite news |publisher=US Citt\u00e0 di Palermo |language=Italian |accessdate=26 February 2013 |date=24 February 2013 |url=http://palermocalcio.it/it/1213/news/scheda.php?id=28121 |title=ESONERATO MALESANI, RICHIAMATO GASPERINI |trans-title=MALESANI SACKED, GASPERINI RECALLED |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227012556/http://palermocalcio.it/it/1213/news/scheda.php?id=28121 |archive-date=27 February 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Sassuolo===\nOn 29 January 2014, it was announced Malesani has agreed to take over as new manager of the top-flight team [[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Malesani tasked with reviving Sassuolo fortunes|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=ita/news/newsid=2048399.html |publisher= UEFA.com |date= 29 January 2014 |accessdate=8 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|9 March 2014}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n!rowspan=2! width=100|Team\n!rowspan=2! width=50|Nat\n!rowspan=2! width=90|From\n!rowspan=2! width=90|To\n!colspan=8|Record\n|-\n!width=30|G\n!width=30|W\n!width=30|D\n!width=30|L\n!width=50|Win %\n!width=40|GF\n!width=40|GA\n!width=40|+/-\n|-\n|align=left|[[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|1 June 1993{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|30 June 1997\n| 155 || 52 || 66 || 37 || {{#expr: 52/155 * 100 round 2}} ||170||140||+30\n|-\n|align=left|[[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|1 July 1997{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|30 June 1998{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 40 || 18 || 15 || 7 || {{#expr: 18/40 * 100 round 2}} ||74||41||+33\n|-\n|align=left|[[Parma F.C.|Parma]]\n|{{flagicon